All of the roads in Yosemite National Park are scenic, but the most famous scenic drive is along the Tioga Road, a 46-mile (62 km) drive from Crane Flat to Tioga Pass. The road is typically open from late May or early June through sometime in November. ( [Check current road conditions](https://www.nps.gov/yose/planyourvisit/conditions.htm).)
The _Yosemite Road Guide_, available at visitor center [bookstores](https://shop.yosemite.org/) _,_ contains descriptions of each road inside the park and includes suggestions of where to stop along the way.
Some typical driving times from Yosemite Valley:
- Wawona/Mariposa Grove: about an hour
- Glacier Point: about an hour
- Crane Flat: 30 minutes
- Hodgdon Meadow/Big Oak Flat Entrance: 45 minutes
- Hetch Hetchy: 1.5 hours
- Tuolumne Meadows: 1.5 hours
- Tioga Pass: 1.75 hours

### Travel the Yosemite roads in and around Yosemite National Park to experience the most inspiring scenic drives and to see the breathtaking vistas of the Sierra Nevada Mountains.

Yosemite driving tours are numerous. You can enjoy all the beauty of the region in and around Yosemite National Park from the comfort of your own vehicle.

### [Yosemite Valley Loop](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/yosemite_valley_loop.php)

Of all Yosemite drives, the Yosemite Valley loop is the most popular. The awesome landscapes show you why this park is so famous for its views. Although the valley is usually crowded, it’s a must-see when you come to the park.

### [Tioga Road](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/tioga_road.php)

Of course, you can take your pick of any one of the Yosemite National Park roads, but don’t leave out the Tioga Road. Traveling over Tioga Pass is something to experience, and you’ll also find a great many opportunities for some outdoor fun along the way.

### [Wawona Road](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/wawona_road.php)

When traveling the Wawona Road, you will want to stop at the Mariposa Grove to see the Giant Sequoias, and in Wawona, an Old West town with hiking trails and a Pioneer History Center to explore.

### [Glacier Point Road](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/glacier_point_road.php)

Glacier Point Road is one of the Yosemite Park roads that leads you to some stellar views of the valley and the sights that make Yosemite so popular. You’ll find hiking trails all along the way so you can get out and stretch and get some exercise in the fresh mountain air.

### [Big Oak Flat Road](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/big_oak_flat_road.php)

Start your journey along Big Oak Flat Road by visiting the Merced Grove of Giant Sequoias, then stop off at the Tuolumne Grove to see more, with a great self-guided trail that will further enhance your visit.

### [El Portal Road](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/el_portal_road.php)

Along El Portal Drive, between the Yosemite Valley and El Portal, California, you will marvel at the sights, particularly the Merced River Canyon in the spring when the wildflowers are in bloom. Enjoy outdoor activities such as hiking and rafting.

### [Hetch Hetchy Road](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/hetch_hetchy_road.php)

At the end of the Hetch Hetchy Road you’ll discover the Hetch Hetchy Reservoir and the O’Shaughnessy Dam where you can embark on hikes to see cascading waterfalls.

### [Sierra Vista Byway](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/sierra_vista_scenic_byway.php)

This byway travels through meadows and forests, past towering peaks and huge granite outcroppings. Visit unique sights along the way, including the Ross Cabin, Mammoth Pool and Mile High Vista.

### [Highway 108](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/highway_108.php)

Travel from Sonora, California to Bridgeport on a route that offers breathtaking scenery. You will see the Columns of the Giants in the Stanislaus National Forest and travel over Sonora Pass.

### [Highway 120](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/highway_120.php)

Start at Chinese Camp and travel through the Sierra Nevada region, enjoying the sights as you go. It’s a drive the whole family will enjoy and one you should make when visiting Yosemite National Park.

### [Highway 140](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/highway_140.php)

Along this scenic route, you can stop in the town of El Portal, finding exciting whitewater rafting, hiking and much more. Visit Mariposa, California to see some interesting history contained in its two museums.

### [Highway 4](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/highway_4.php)

This mountainous highway takes you across Ebbetts Pass and gives you access to a number of outdoor activities.

### [Highway 41](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/highway_41.php)

From Yosemite to Oakhurst, California is a short yet inspiring drive with plenty to do along the way. Ride the Sugar Pine Railroad, fish in Bass Lake. The fun never ends.

### [Highway 49](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/highway_49.php)

Here you will discover 100 miles of scenic beauty as you travel the route of the 49ers of Gold Rush Days. Mining towns and historic sites flourish along the path you’ll take from Oakhurst south of Yosemite to Vinton near Frenchman Lake.

### [Vehicle Restrictions](https://www.allyosemite.com/scenic_drives/vehicle_restrictions.php)

You should always be aware of all vehicle restrictions when you are traveling to Yosemite National Park, so your trip will be safe and trouble-free.

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Tioga-Lake-1.jpg)

Tioga Road over Tioga Pass is located in the eastern portion of Yosemite National Park and provides a way to drive through the park’s high country, connecting [Yosemite Valley](https://californiathroughmylens.com/yosemite-national-park-guide) with Highway 395.It was built in the late 1930s and is the highest highway pass in California. While many people visit Yosemite Valley, far fewer take the time to make this drive, which is one of the best in California.

During the winter, this road gets snowed in and is not passable, but during the summer its 45-mile length provides an adventure all on its own. Traveling this highway will take you from the base of Yosemite Valley at 4,000 feet of elevation all the way up, and over the pass the road is named for at around 10,000 feet of elevation. These elevation changes provide beautiful views and vistas, so make sure you take your time and to pull out when the road shows you something beautiful, which is often. Below are some of my favorite stops in order from Yosemite Valley to [Highway 395](https://californiathroughmylens.com/highway-395-roadtrip).

### **Tuolumne Grove**

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/tuolumne-grove-17-640x427.jpg)

Tuolumne Grove is the first stop you will get to when you turn onto Tioga Road. This grove has a dozen or so giant sequoias and it is a great hike for the whole family, even featuring a tree you can walk through. You can read all about it [here](https://californiathroughmylens.com/tuolumne-grove-yosemite-summer).

### **North Dome – Porcupine Creek Trailhead**

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/north-dome-14-640x427.jpg)

If you are looking for a fantastic half day hike, then this is a great option. The hike to North Dome takes you through the forest and out to a granite slab that has fantastic views of Half Dome. You can also see Indian Arch on the hike, which one of the few rock arches in Yosemite. Read more about it [here](https://californiathroughmylens.com/north-dome-yosemite/).

### Lukens Lake

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/lukens-lake-7-640x427.jpg)

Lukens Lake is a short 1-mile hike to a beautiful meadow and lake. This short hike goes uphill the whole way and takes you to another stunning lake along the drive. It is not very busy, so you can often have the lake all to yourself.

### May Lake

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/may-lake-9-640x427.jpg)

May Lake is an easily accessible high altitude lake that sits at the base of Mt Hoffman. Hiking from the parking lot is a short 1.2 miles each way, and the lake provides an incredible payoff, especially in the summer. Read about it [here](https://californiathroughmylens.com/may-lake/).

### Olmsted Point

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Olmsted-Point.jpg)

Olmsted Point is a pullout about 20 miles from Yosemite Valley and roughly half way along the Tioga Road drive . It has a great view of the surrounding area, which is covered in sparse trees and granite.

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Tioga-Pass-3.jpg)

You can scramble up a small rock and even see views of [Clouds Rest](https://californiathroughmylens.com/clouds-rest) and [Half Dome](https://californiathroughmylens.com/hiking-half-dome-photo-guide) far in the distance, as well as a lot of the backcountry Yosemite wilderness only accessible by hiking.

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Half-Dome-from-Olmsted-Point.jpg)

### Tenaya Lake

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Tenya-Lake.jpg)

As you make your way from Olmsted Point, you will immediately notice Tenaya Lake appearing in the distance. This lake is dotted with campsites along its shores. It is breathtaking and provides a serene and relaxing retreat that you would not expect to see so close to civilization.

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Tenya-Lake-3.jpg)

During the summer months, when it is hot, the water is refreshing enough to take a dip in, fish at, or paddle a kayak over.

### Tuolumne Meadows

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Tuolumne-Meadows.jpg)

This lush meadow jumps out at you after a bend in the road, and it stretches as far as the eye can see. It is often so green and beautiful that you won’t have a choice but to stop and take pictures or walk along one of the many trails. The meadows also have a small lodge and a lot of camping if you want to spend a couple of days there, hiking and fishing.

**Soda Springs**

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/soda-springs-6-640x427.jpg)

Soda Springs is one of the most popular hikes in the Tuolumne Meadows region, mostly because it is easy and lets you walk through the meadow on the way to the spring.

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/soda-springs-4-640x427.jpg)

The springs are located inside a small cabin and are almost continuously boiling. I wouldn’t say this is a must-stop attraction, but if you are looking to walk a little, check it out.

### Lembert Dome

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/lembert-dome-1-640x427.jpg)

On the east side of Tuolumne Meadows, there is a granite slab much like Half Dome but much smaller in size. Lembert Dome provides a stark contrast with the earthy tones of the meadows and the grays of the granite dome. Accessible via a moderate hike, the summit offers fantastic views of the road below. Read about the hike [here](https://californiathroughmylens.com/lembert-dome).

### Tioga Pass

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Tioga-Pass-Entry-640x445.jpg)

The pass itself is the official entry point to Yosemite from the east side. If you are entering from here, you will need to pay the park fee, but just for a day driving Tioga Pass alone, it is worth it. This is also the highest point on this road, and here you will be close to 10,000 feet.

### **Tioga Lake**

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Tioga-Lake-1-640x427.jpg)

Tioga Lake is probably my favorite lake on the entire drive. The views from here are stunning with Mt Dana in the distance. There is also a campground here as well.

### Ellery Lake

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Ellery-Lake.jpg)

Right before you start your steep descent into the Lee Vining area, there is one last lake you can turn out at. This lake allows you to spend some time walking around or just to sit and think about the fantastic experience and beauty you drove through.

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Tioga-Pass-5.jpg)

### Whoa Nellie Deli

![](https://californiathroughmylens.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/whoa-nelli-deli-1-640x480.jpg)

As you reach the bottom of Tioga Road and connect with Highway 395, be sure to stop at the Mobil Gas Station, which has the popular Whoa Nelli Deli. This spot is perfect for lunch and one of the most loved restaurants along this portion of Highway 395. Read more [here](https://californiathroughmylens.com/whoa-nellie-deli).

My high school buddy and I drove the Tioga Pass Road (as it was called then) as part of our 5 week west coast trip in 1950. Our home was near Chicago and this was our high school graduation present from our families The road was gravel. narrow. twisty and kinda scary for these flatlanders. Our old 1941 Chevrolet would overheat about every 10 minutes (The elevation and unpressurized radiator) Fortunately, little waterfalls would appear along side the road about each time and we could replace the boiled out water. We made it....slowly. I recall we camped in one of those beautiful valleys but don't remember the name. My friend and I still talk about that trip and the pass.

The drive on the 41 is mostly through forest; there's not really that much in the way of scenery other than the trees, until you get to " [Tunnel View](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g61000-d593212-Reviews-Tunnel_View-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html)" now known as " [Yosemite Valley](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g61000-d489919-Reviews-Yosemite_Valley-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html) Overlook." That is right after you come out of the very long [Wawona](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g61000-d248059-Reviews-Wawona_Hotel-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html) Tunnel. That is one of the most famous views of Yosemite Valley. All of Yosemite Valley is intensely scenic, probably the highest concentration of beauty in the world. Also very scenic is the drive up to [Glacier Point](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g61000-d139187-Reviews-Glacier_Point-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html), and Washburn Point just before it, which faces east, then Glacier Point, which faces north. You could also consider taking the relatively short hike to the top of Sentinel Dome, for a panoramic 360-degree "top of the world" view of the park. That is off of Glacier Point Road. In addition to the amazing landscape and scenery of Yosemite Valley, you will want to take a drive along Tioga Road through the park, and that is also intensely scenic, though in a different way, as that reaches high elevations (almost to 10,000 feet at [Tioga Pass](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g61000-d146103-Reviews-Tioga_Pass-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html)) and you are right in the middle of the High Sierras. There are turnouts and sights and views all along the way. Olmstead Point is a stop where you will get a view that includes the back side of [Half Dome](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g61000-d139183-Reviews-Half_Dome-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html). I would even go past the east gate of the park as far as Ellery Lake which is right next to the road and spectacular as well. There are tons of places to take photos in Yosemite, it's not like other national parks where you drive and drive to get to a feature, then drive and drive more. The roads in [Yosemite](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Tourism-g61000-Yosemite_National_Park_California-Vacations.html) are highly scenic the entire way; there's very little in the way of filler, but on Highway 41 you will mostly just see trees until you get to the Wawona Tunnel.

Thank you Curmudgeon for the tip regarding the [Yosemite](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Tourism-g61000-Yosemite_National_Park_California-Vacations.html) Road Guide.

I ordered it from Amazon. It was only a few dollars including a shipping fee. It's a great guide. It has points of interested with the specific mile marker indicated - down to the 10th of a mile. I think it was definitely worth ordering in advance as there is a lot of information to cover.

It also shows where the one way roads are in the Valley. I found several maps on the internet but they didn't show where the one way roads are.

Another thing I didn't know is that there are roadside markers along the main roads. This guide explains how the letter & numbering system works.

If anyone is planning on siteseeing by car in Yosemite, I highly recommend ordering this in advance. I will only have 4 days in Yosemite so it wouldn't be practical to wait till I got there to study it. So anyone else who has limited time might want this.

I like Hwy 41 as well, but it doesn't have the views that some Park roads have. It does have quite a few turn-outs (easy to stop for some solitude), several creek crossings (Mosquito, Alder, Bishop, Strawberry, Rail, & Indian) between [Wawona](https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g61000-d248059-Reviews-Wawona_Hotel-Yosemite_National_Park_California.html) & Chinquapin, the helicopter landing, and lots of bearclover (also called Mountain Misery or Chamaebatia foliolosa.) I think the bearclover provides the predominant aroma; some books refer to its aroma as "pungent".
